<subSubSection id="FBADF1141F64BEE66D7FE6D1589ACCA7" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="777E93FA26988E4E69B41CCFF7CFB8A1" pageId="12" pageNumber="119" type="mainText">
Remarks: This species is variable. All specimens from northern Zimbabwe have cell r 
<sub id="12F002614ACC167DFDA249D8E666E0AD" pageId="12" pageNumber="119">5</sub>
widely open, whereas this cell is closed in the material from Botswana. The very long maxillary palpi are a good character for identification of the species. There are certain similarities to 
<taxonomicName id="AC3ACDB1CA9232B889945029C7C38E4A" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Oratostylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Oratostylum</taxonomicName>
, for example the elongated palpi and the well pronounced facial swelling, but we treat 
<taxonomicName id="BE53CEDE2A7899241E472AF92223E518" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Oratostylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="12" pageNumber="119" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipalpus">longipalpus</taxonomicName>
as a species of Remotomyia because of the strong macrosetae on the pronotum and postpronotal lobes, and the strong anteriorly directed setae on T
<quantity id="72227EBE0227CC45DB18C6CF6C3A338D" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.651" metricValueMax="1.778" metricValueMin="1.524" unit="in" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6-7 in</quantity>
females.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
